2 Question A

Plot the selected time series and comment the general features you can observe.

# Plot the Australian tourist data
ggplot(tourist) + 
  geom_line(aes(Time,Tourists), color = "#964B00") + 
  labs(title = "Nights Spent by International Tourists", x = "Time", y = "Tourists (MM)") + 
  theme_light()

There are four components considered when analyzing time series data:

• Trend: A long-term increase or decrease in the data; a “changing direction”.

• Seasonality: A seasonal pattern of a fixed and known period. If the frequency is unchanging and associated with some aspect of the calendar, then the pattern is seasonal.

• Cycle: A rise and fall pattern not of a fixed frequency. If the fluctuations are not of a fixed frequency, then they are cyclic.

• Random: Remainder of what is not included in the other three components.

Note: Seasonal vs Cyclic: In general, cyclic patterns are longer and more variable than seasonal patterns.

From these main elements, we notice several observations. The trend appears to be generally increasing. Strong seasonality occurs because of the relative structure of how each year follows a very similar pattern. Since the data is from Australia, their busiest seasons are their warmer months. This would include the first and fourth quarters. In the first five years, the seasonality component is different than anything past 2005 Q1. Real life events such as the 2000 Sydney Olympics and 2003 Rugby World Cup could have played an important role. This can be seen through the amplitudes stagnation during those couple of years when those festivities stopped in 2003. If there is presence of cyclic behavior, it would be difficult to see since seasonality dominates the series. Other than cyclic behavior being hard to analyze or non-existent, the random fluctuations should be reviewed a different way.

Since the size of the seasonal and randomness amplitudes between periods continues to increase with the level of time series, a multiplicative model may be the best method. To quickly check this, a transformation of the series can be calculated that shows the following:

# Log transformation of Tourist

By transforming the ‘Tourists’ variable, this can help stabilize the variance (randomness). This is easily seen by how the amplitudes for seasonality become more consistent over time since they appear to increase at a slower rate, if at all.

Seasonal Plot
According to Chapter 2.4, a seasonal plot mimics a time plot except that the data are plotted against the individual “seasons.” Within the Seasonal Plot, there is data from each season that can overlap. As mentioned earlier, the summer months for Australia are their peak seasons. Therefore, Q1 and Q4 have much more overnight tourists than Q2 and Q3. As the series evolves, the change from one season to another is more drastic. For example, analyze the bottom red line from Q1 to Q2 and compare that same time period to the most recent year, 2015. The change between those periods significantly widened. Similar effects can be seen between Q2 to Q3 and Q3 to Q4, but they are not as prominent. Overall, this plot paints a clear picture, identifying years that seasonality changes.

Seasonal Subseries Plot
An additional chart that represents seasonality is the Seasonal Subseries Plot. For each quarter, the data are collected together in separate mini time plots. From Chapter 2.5, the book outlines that the blue horizontal lines indicate the means for each aggregated period. Once again, fourth quarter is superior compared to the other seasons.

Lag Plot
The scatterplot shows the quarterly night visitors spent by international tourists to Australia. The horizontal axis shows lagged values of the time series. Each graph shows \(y_t\) against \(y_{t-k}\) for various values of \(k\) and the colors indicate the quarters. There appears to be strong relationship at lags 4 and 6, which demonstrates the strong seasonality in the data.

Autocorrelation Plot
Chapter 2.8 states that autocorrelation measures the linear relationship between lagged values of a time series. Prior to plotting the autocorrelation, there is a tsibble object that corresponds to the nine scatterplots. We typically plot the ACF to see how the correlations change with the lag \(k\). Within the correlogram, it is seen that the autocorrelations are larger for the seasonal lags which occur quarterly. Additionally, when a trend is present, which is the case here, the autocorrelations for small lags tend to be large and positive. This can be observed at \(r^4\), \(r^8\), \(r^{12}\) and \(r^{16}\), representing the quarters. There appears to be no white noise which would mean the time series shows no autocorrelation.

Classical decomposition has two forms, additive and multiplicative. We will start with analyzing the additive approach (\(y_t = S_t + T_t + R_t\)). Each structure can describe a time series with seasonal period \(m\), which would be \(m = 4\) for the the international visitors spending nights in Australia on a quarterly basis. Specific to seasonality, it is assumed that the component is constant year to year. Since \(m\) is an even number, the trend-cycle element \(\hat{T_t}\) needs to be computed using 2 x \(m\)-MA. Once that value is found, the detrended series can be found through \(y_t - \hat{T_t}\). To find \(\hat{S_t}\), average the detrended values for that season, which should be applied to ensure that they add to zero. Those components then are summed for each year of the data. Having those two main components, the remainder can be estimated: \(\hat{R_t}\ = y_t - \hat{T_t}\ - \hat{S_t}\).

The trend is mostly linear and positive after five-ish years from 2000. Towards the end of the slope though in 2015, there appears to be a steeper incline which could be due to a multiplicative effect. The seasonality remains consistent, which is not supposed to be the case. The random component though shows signs of patterns, which is problematic because we want to isolate the components since we want to know what cannot be explained.

The multiplicative decomposition (\(y_t = S_t*T_t*R_t\)) is similar to additive in the fact that the \(m\) is even, but it ends up fitting better with the seasonal effect on the amplitudes. This means that it takes into consideration the proportional seasonal fluctuations. These are sometimes referred to as ‘seasonal indices.’ In addition, they both have in common that the first and last two values are not shown. This is because the trend is extracted using a moving average of order 4 (\(2 x 4-MA\)). Earlier in the analysis, the reader can clearly see the divergent trend. Again, there is a steeper slope around 2015 that will be considered at a later point. According to Slide 26, the detrended series is \(z_t = y_t /T_t\). The seasonality still appears to be constant across time but the randomness does not have patterns. When adding those three components together, they can reconstruct the top panel. Therefore, we would assume the multiplicative model fits better due to the true randomness.

Note: Keep in mind that classical decomposition is not recommended when choosing a method. Please see Section 3.4 for more details. Therefore, other models will be explored.

Although we will not dive into \(m\)-MA, I wanted to give a quick outline of moving averages of moving averages since we need to make an even-order moving average symmetric if additional analyses were to be conducted. Section 3.3 mentions how using “a 2-MA follows a moving average of an even order (such as 4), it is called a ‘centered moving average of order 4.’”

Here is the transformed Australian quarterly international night tourists with the \(\lambda\) (0.06) parameter chosen using the Guerrero method. Section 3.1 outlines that a “good value of \(\lambda\) is one which makes the size of the seasonal variation about the same across the whole series, as that makes the forecasting model simpler.”

# SLT additive decomposition, 3.6 SLT Decomposition
tourist |> 
    model(
      STL(log(Tourists) ~ trend(window = 5) + season(window = 5),  # 5 due to quarterly data
          robust = TRUE)) -> decomp_stl_mult

stl_mult <- components(decomp_stl_mult) #season_adjust = y_t - s_t

stl_mult |>  autoplot() + theme_light()

Compared to the classical decompositions, the STL is a robust and versatile method. There are additional features that can be used within the function, giving the flexibility to alter the parameters to see how the trend-cycle and seasonal change the time series components. These two windows can be described as the following:

• Trend-cycle window: The number of consecutive observations to be used when estimating the trend-cycle

• Season window: The number of consecutive years to be used in estimating each value in the seasonal component

For both parameters, an odd number should be used. Also, note that a smaller value will allow for more rapid changes. For instance, we increasing the trend window to 68, we obtain just a straight line.

The STL model uses an additive approach. Earlier in the classical decomposition, there was an issue with the random component in the additive method due to patterns in the remainder. Therefore, it is important to also obtain a multiplicative model. To create this model, one needs to take the ‘logs of the data then back-transforming the components’ because the data shows variation that increases with the level of the series. Within both SLT models, the trend is positive. But, when comparing SLT versus SLT transformed, they have different peaks or dips that are more distinct depending on which model is used. The seasonality of the additive STL continues to grow as the amplitude increases over time while the multiplicative takes that more into account. With the log transformed model, the seasonal pattern slightly changes from Q3 to Q4 because it appears to be more constant when the series continues. The random component in the second approach does not show any patterns while the additive method does. Out of the four models, the STL multiplicative method may be the most relevant since the seasonal variation increases over time.

4 Question C

Argument your model’s choice and further justify it by performing a residuals analysis and validating the model’s assumptions using the required statistical testing procedures.

For each ETS method, there exists two models: one with additive errors and another with multiplicative errors. We will explore both as they generate different prediction intervals even though the point forecasts are identical if using the same smoothing parameter values. Although it is already known that the data contains trend and seasonality, some of these models will immediately not produce the best models (SES and Holt), but they are still explained to demonstrate the logic.

The simple exponential smoothing method is best suited for forecasting data with no obvious trend or seasonality. Between the two models, the better one in this scenario seems to be the SES(M,N,N) because it has a lower BIC measure. Both RMSE’s are around 8.32, and it is assumed that other models will be an improvement. Within these methods, there is a smoothing parameter, \(\alpha\). • Forecast equation: \(\hat{y}_{t+h|t} = l_t\)
• Level equation: \(l_t = {\alpha}{y_t} + (1 - \alpha)l_{t-1}\)

In Holt’s model, this allows the SES to be extended to include the trend within the forecast data. In practice, this means that the forecast function is not considered flat but is trending. According to the book, ’the \(h\)-step-ahead forecast is equal to the last estimated level plus \(h\) times the last estimated trend value. Hence the forecasts are a linear function of \(h\). In addition to the SES equations, Holt’s linear method introduces \(\beta\), the slope.

• Forecast equation: \(\hat{y}_{t+h|t} = l_t\)
• Level equation: \(l_t = {\alpha}{y_t} + (1 - \alpha)l_{t-1}\)
• Trend equation: \(b_t = {\beta}*({l_t} - l_{t-1})\)

Right away, we intuitively know that Holt’s model will be better than SES because it includes trend. If we compare to the previous two models, the BICs slightly dropped as did the RMSEs. It is interesting though because the RMSE of the multiplicative model is slightly higher than additive here. When looking at the multiplicative decomposition for classical and STL, these models seemed to fit better than additive. We will continue to explore.

Thee additional smoothing parameter for slope is \(\beta\). Values close to 0 means that the trend does not change often in either model. \(\alpha\) is very small too, indicating that the level does not change rapidly in order to capture the trended series. Since seasonality within the model is known and there are additional models to run, including a damped trend here will not be done at the moment. Instead, this constant trend will be discussed in the Holt Winter’s section.

As a quick recap, SES did not account for trend or seasonality, and Holt’s method only included trend. As seen throughout this entire analysis, trend and seasonality have been present. Therefore, there will be no additional measurements to consider.

Now, we dive into Holt-Winters method which captures seasonality. There is one more smoothing parameter, \(\gamma\) which accounts for the seasonal component, \(s_t\). According to Chapter 8.3, the additive method is preferred when the seasonal variations are roughly constant through the series, while the multiplicative method is used primarily when those variations are changing proportional to the level of the series. The additive model will express the seasonal component in absolute terms while the other will denote in relative terms (percentages). It has been acknowledged that the amplitude has been increasing over time, and therefore, we could assume this would be the best model out any previous method considered. To verify this, we run multiple Holt-Winters models and compare AIC, AICc, BIC, RMSE, and residuals (only for Holt-Winters methods) relative to all other models.

This model will not be considered since the seasonality has variations that are changing proportional to the level of the time series.

After running more models with these error and trend combinations, the best model proved to be the Holt-Winters (A, M, M). There are several comments about this method:

• The trend appears to be increasing in the beginning of the series, but decreases after several years. Then, it maintains a more or less constant slope. In 2015 though, there is that slight uptick again. This is one of the main reasons this multiplicative trend was selected.

• The model has been identified as having a quarterly season pattern.

• The remainder does not show any patterns.

The smoothing parameters can be described as:

• \(\alpha\): At 0.23, there is more weight given to observations from the more distant past.

• \(\beta\): A very small value indicates that the trend does not change often.

• \(\gamma\): The parameter has a small number, meaning that the older values in X direction are weighted more heavily.

Below shows the component form for the the multiplicative method. For our model though, a certain component will need to be changed later.

• Forecast equation: \(\hat{y}_{t+h|t} = (l_t+ hb_t)s_{t+h-m(k+1)}\)
• Level equation: \(l_t = {\alpha}\frac{y_t}{s_{t-m}} + (1 - \alpha)(l_{t-1} + b_{t-1})\)
• Trend equation: \(b_t = {\beta}^*({l_t} - l_{t-1}) + (1 - {\beta}^*)b_{t-1}\)
• Seasonal equation: \(s_t = {\gamma}\frac{y_t}{(t_{t-1} + b_{t-1})} + (1 - \gamma)s_{t-m}\)

For this final model, we will review the residuals.

Although checking residuals is not essential for forecasting, it makes calculating the prediction intervals much easier. Therefore, they should be checked to see if they are follow the necessary assumptions. By using the gg_tsresiduals() function, it is seen that the errors look skewed. The correlogram does not show any lags that exceed the dashed blue lines which indicate whether the correlations are significantly different from zero. In addition, the residual plot shows the random scatter of points around zero, revealing constant variance and homoscedasticity.

The QQ Plot of residuals appears to be non-normal due to the points by the tails being far away from the line that represents the expected values. To determine if the residuals are normally distributed, we run a statistical test, Shapiro-Wilk. The null hypothesis is that the errors are normally distributed. Since the p-value is less than \(\alpha\) at 0.05, there is enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. The residuals can be assumed to not be normally distributed. Overall, forecasts from this method may be good, but the prediction intervals may be inaccurate since we do not have normality.

4.12 Forecast Error Comparison

According to Chapter 3.4, forecast “error” is the difference between an observed value and its forecast. “Error” does not mean a mistake, but the unpredictable part of an observation. It can be written as: \(e_{T+h} = y_{T+h} - \hat{y}_{T+h|T}\).

In this section, we will compare all models relative to their AIC, AICc, BIC, RMSE, and Sharpio-Wilk values to ensure that the final model was the best fit and how the forecast errors look against each other.

According to Chapter 5.5, a prediction interval gives an interval within which we expect \(y_t\) to lie within a specified probability. Although the distribution is non-normal, we can still calculate the future observations through \(\hat{y}_{T+h|T} \pm c\hat{\sigma}_h\). The faint white line (point forecast) in the middle of the shaded areas is the forecast for the next 2.5 years, which captured the historical seasonal pattern. Those ten periods are based on the Holt_Winters (A,M,M) model since this proved to be the best method. This forecast uses various levels, such as 80, 90, 95, and 99. Relating to all of those percentages, each have a multiplier, \(c\), that have different values. For example, the multiplier for 95% is 1.96 and 99% is 2.58. On the other hand, there are a couple underestimates like towards the end of the provided data in 2015. Overall, the prediction intervals display the uncertainty in forecasts. Since these are expected to be accurate, those intervals will be more narrow.

6 Question E

Compute a h = 10 forecast and prediction intervals for the same levels of the previous point, this time by using bootstrapping: a) assuming normality of residuals and b) sampling based on your fitted model’s residuals.

As stated earlier, the basis of the state space model equation for the ETS(A, M, M) will be a majority multiplicative, but the level will be additive. This is the component form:

• Forecast equation: \(y_t= l_{t-1}b_{t-1}s_{t-m}+ \epsilon_t\)
• Level equation: \(l_t = l_{t-1}b_{t-1} + \frac{{\alpha}{\epsilon_t}}{s_{t-m}}\)
• Trend equation: \(b_t = b_{t-1} + \frac{{\beta}{\epsilon_t}}{({s_{t-m}}l_{t-1})}\)
• Seasonal equation: \(s_t = s_{t-m} + \frac{{\gamma}{\epsilon_t}}{(l_{t-1}b_{t-1})}\)

In Section 1.7, it outlines that what we are trying to forecast is unknown and can think of it as a random variable. Therefore, we can utilize the method of bootstrapping. It is used for a time series in order to simulate future values of a series using a model by the residuals. Sometimes, this is used because the normal distribution does not fit to the errors. From the residual analysis earlier for the final model, it had a non-normal distribution. The idea is to draw at random the new error from the sample of estimated errors with replacement. Instead of simulating with normality, we simulate a random sample of independent errors from the set with equal probability. Since there are many samples, this gives Australia an insight of how many international tourists they should expect in the next ten quarters. By applying this method, it can help the country quantify uncertainty in the near future to combat any potential challenges from the historical data that was previously collected. Additionally, bootstrapping would allow the analyst to know the prediction intervals which are based on a normal distribution. There were four prediction intervals that are included: 80, 90, 95, and 99.

L72 <- components(tourist_AMM)$level[72]

These nine values were extracted for the state space model. Since this model has seasonlity, the calculation for that component is not exact, but close to the best representation of how it should be modeled by accoutning for each of the seasons individually.

h.step <- 10      # number of steps ahead for forecast
R <- 100    # number of repetitions

# creating empty matrices that will be filled as we make computations
l.mat <- matrix(nrow = h.step, ncol = R)
b.mat <- matrix(nrow = h.step, ncol = R)
y <- matrix(nrow = h.step, ncol = R)

# initialization of y_31, b_31 and l_31 for h = 1
# set the random seed to have always the same random numbers generation 
set.seed(1)
eps <- sample(residuals, size = R, replace = TRUE)

y[1,]  <- L72*B72*S69 + eps
l.mat[1,] <- L72*B72 + alpha*eps/S69
b.mat[1,] <- B72 + beta*eps/(S69*L72)

# the loop for the next steps, h = 2 to h = h.step (10 here)

for (h in 2:h.step) {
  
  set.seed(h)
  eps <- sample(residuals, size = R, replace = TRUE)
  
  forecast_row = 72 + h
  # 69 mod 4 = 1
  # 70 mod 4 = 2
  # 71 mod 4 = 3
  # 72 mod 4 = 0
  
  if (forecast_row %% 4 == 1) {
    season_coeff = S69
  } else if (forecast_row %% 4 == 2) {
    season_coeff = S70
  } else if (forecast_row %% 4 == 3) {
    season_coeff = S71
  } else if (forecast_row %% 4 == 0) {
    season_coeff = S72
  }
  
  y[h,]     <- l.mat[h-1,]*b.mat[h-1,]*season_coeff + eps
  l.mat[h,] <- l.mat[h-1,]*b.mat[h-1,] + alpha*eps/season_coeff
  b.mat[h,] <- b.mat[h-1,] + beta*eps/(season_coeff*l.mat[h-1,])
}

plot(x = 1:68, y = tourist$Tourists,
     xlim=c(0, 80), ylim=c(0, 90),
     type='l', lwd=1,
     main = "Bootstrap 1,000 Errors " , xlab = "Quarter", ylab = "Australian Night Tourists (MM)")

# Loop for the repetition of the forecast
for(j in c(1:R)) { 
  points(x = 69:78, y = y[,j], type = "l", lwd = 1, col="#964B00")
}
